 Build Timeline of User/Device Interaction with Timesketch
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Extract device interaction data from Autopsy forensic analysis
Install and configure Timesketch for timeline analysis
Import forensic data into Timesketch
Build comprehensive timelines of user and device interactions
Analyze timeline data to identify patterns and suspicious activities
Prerequisites
Basic understanding of Linux command line operations
Familiarity with digital forensics concepts
Knowledge of file system structures
Understanding of log file formats
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated environment. The provided Linux machine is bare metal with no pre-installed tools, so you will install all required software during the lab.

Task 1: Extract Device Interaction Data from Autopsy
Subtask 1.1: Install Autopsy
# Update system packages
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

# Install Java (required for Autopsy)
sudo apt install openjdk-11-jdk -y

# Download and install Autopsy
wget https://github.com/sleuthkit/autopsy/releases/download/autopsy-4.20.0/autopsy-4.20.0.zip
unzip autopsy-4.20.0.zip
cd autopsy-4.20.0
Subtask 1.2: Create Sample Forensic Data
# Create a sample disk image for analysis
mkdir ~/forensic_data
cd ~/forensic_data

# Create a sample file system with user activity
dd if=/dev/zero of=sample_disk.img bs=1M count=100
mkfs.ext4 sample_disk.img

# Mount and populate with sample data
mkdir mount_point
sudo mount -o loop sample_disk.img mount_point

# Create sample user activity files
sudo mkdir -p mount_point/home/user1/{Documents,Downloads,Desktop}
sudo touch mount_point/home/user1/Documents/report.txt
sudo touch mount_point/home/user1/Downloads/software.zip
echo "Sample web history" | sudo tee mount_point/home/user1/.bash_history

# Create system logs
sudo mkdir -p mount_point/var/log
echo "$(date): User login event" | sudo tee mount_point/var/log/auth.log
echo "$(date): File access event" | sudo tee mount_point/var/log/syslog

sudo umount mount_point
Subtask 1.3: Analyze with Autopsy
# Start Autopsy
cd ~/autopsy-4.20.0/bin
./autopsy

# Note: Autopsy will start on localhost:9999
# Access via web browser at http://localhost:9999
Manual Steps in Autopsy Web Interface:

Create new case named "UserDeviceTimeline"
Add data source: select the sample_disk.img file
Run ingest modules: File Type Identification, Hash Lookup, Keyword Search
Export timeline data to CSV format from the Timeline view
Subtask 1.4: Export Timeline Data
# Create export directory
mkdir ~/timeline_exports

# Export data from Autopsy (this would be done through the web interface)
# For this lab, we'll create sample timeline data
cat > ~/timeline_exports/autopsy_timeline.csv << 'EOF'
timestamp,source,type,description,file_path
2024-01-15T10:30:00Z,filesystem,file_created,Document created,/home/user1/Documents/report.txt
2024-01-15T10:35:00Z,filesystem,file_accessed,File accessed,/home/user1/Documents/report.txt
2024-01-15T11:00:00Z,system,login,User login event,/var/log/auth.log
2024-01-15T11:15:00Z,filesystem,file_downloaded,Software downloaded,/home/user1/Downloads/software.zip
2024-01-15T11:30:00Z,system,command,Command executed,/home/user1/.bash_history
EOF
Task 2: Build and Analyze Timeline using Timesketch
Subtask 2.1: Install Timesketch Dependencies
# Install Python and pip
sudo apt install python3 python3-pip python3-venv -y

# Install Docker for Timesketch
sudo apt install docker.io docker-compose -y
sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl enable docker
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER

# Logout and login again for docker group changes
newgrp docker
Subtask 2.2: Deploy Timesketch
# Clone Timesketch repository
cd ~
git clone https://github.com/google/timesketch.git
cd timesketch

# Start Timesketch using Docker Compose
docker-compose up -d

# Wait for services to start
sleep 60

# Check if services are running
docker-compose ps
Subtask 2.3: Access and Configure Timesketch
# Create initial user account
docker-compose exec timesketch-web tsctl create-user admin --password admin123

# Access Timesketch web interface at http://localhost:5000
echo "Timesketch is available at: http://localhost:5000"
echo "Username: admin"
echo "Password: admin123"
Subtask 2.4: Prepare Timeline Data for Import
# Convert CSV to Timesketch-compatible format
cat > ~/timeline_exports/timesketch_timeline.jsonl << 'EOF'
{"message": "Document created: /home/user1/Documents/report.txt", "timestamp": 1705316200, "datetime": "2024-01-15T10:30:00+00:00", "source_short": "filesystem", "source_long": "File System Activity"}
{"message": "File accessed: /home/user1/Documents/report.txt", "timestamp": 1705316500, "datetime": "2024-01-15T10:35:00+00:00", "source_short": "filesystem", "source_long": "File System Activity"}
{"message": "User login event", "timestamp": 1705318000, "datetime": "2024-01-15T11:00:00+00:00", "source_short": "system", "source_long": "System Events"}
{"message": "Software downloaded: /home/user1/Downloads/software.zip", "timestamp": 1705318900, "datetime": "2024-01-15T11:15:00+00:00", "source_short": "filesystem", "source_long": "File System Activity"}
{"message": "Command executed in bash history", "timestamp": 1705319800, "datetime": "2024-01-15T11:30:00+00:00", "source_short": "system", "source_long": "System Events"}
EOF
Subtask 2.5: Import Timeline into Timesketch
# Copy timeline file to Timesketch container
docker cp ~/timeline_exports/timesketch_timeline.jsonl timesketch-web:/tmp/

# Import timeline using tsctl
docker-compose exec timesketch-web tsctl import-timeline \
  --timeline_name "User Device Interaction Timeline" \
  --sketch_id 1 \
  /tmp/timesketch_timeline.jsonl
Subtask 2.6: Analyze Timeline Data
Manual Analysis Steps in Timesketch Web Interface:

Access Timeline View:

Navigate to http://localhost:5000
Login with admin credentials
Select the created sketch
Apply Filters:

# Filter by source type
source_short:"filesystem"

# Filter by time range
datetime:[2024-01-15T10:00:00 TO 2024-01-15T12:00:00]
Create Analysis Views:

Group events by source type
Sort by timestamp
Identify patterns in user activity
Subtask 2.7: Generate Timeline Report
# Export analysis results
docker-compose exec timesketch-web tsctl export-timeline \
  --sketch_id 1 \
  --timeline_id 1 \
  --output_format csv \
  --output_file /tmp/timeline_analysis.csv

# Copy exported file to host
docker cp timesketch-web:/tmp/timeline_analysis.csv ~/timeline_exports/

# View the analysis results
head -20 ~/timeline_exports/timeline_analysis.csv
Verification Steps
Verify Autopsy Installation
# Check if Autopsy is accessible
curl -s http://localhost:9999 | grep -q "Autopsy" && echo "Autopsy is running" || echo "Autopsy not accessible"
Verify Timesketch Installation
# Check Timesketch services
docker-compose ps | grep -E "(timesketch|elasticsearch|redis)"

# Test API endpoint
curl -s http://localhost:5000/api/v1/version/ | grep -q "version" && echo "Timesketch API is working" || echo "API not responding"
Verify Timeline Data
# Check imported timeline count
wc -l ~/timeline_exports/timesketch_timeline.jsonl

# Verify timeline structure
head -1 ~/timeline_exports/timesketch_timeline.jsonl | python3 -m json.tool
Common Issues and Solutions
Issue: Docker permission denied

# Solution: Add user to docker group and restart session
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
newgrp docker
Issue: Timesketch services not starting

# Solution: Check system resources and restart services
docker-compose down
docker system prune -f
docker-compose up -d
Issue: Timeline import fails

# Solution: Validate JSON format
python3 -c "import json; [json.loads(line) for line in open('~/timeline_exports/timesketch_timeline.jsonl')]"
Cleanup
# Stop Timesketch services
cd ~/timesketch
docker-compose down

# Remove containers and volumes
docker-compose down -v

# Clean up files
rm -rf ~/forensic_data ~/timeline_exports ~/autopsy-4.20.0*
